---
title: Noma — Architecture
audience: contributors
---

# Architecture

::summary
The whole codebase fits in one mental model: source → parser → AST → renderer. There are no plugins, no parser combinators, no build pipelines. This is intentional.
::

## Pipeline

```
.noma source
   │
   ▼  parser.ts
typed AST  ─────────►  validator.ts  ─►  diagnostics
   │
   ▼  renderer-html.ts / renderer-llm.ts / renderer-json.ts
HTML / LLM context / JSON
   │
   ▼  scripts/render-pdf.ts
PDF
```

Each arrow is a pure function. The parser does not validate. The renderers do not parse. The validator does not render.

## Modules

::grid{columns=2}
:::card{title="src/ast.ts"}
The discriminated `Node` union. Every other module imports types from here. Adding a node variant breaks every renderer's exhaustive switch — that is the desired safety property.
:::

:::card{title="src/parser.ts"}
Hand-written line-based recursive descent. ~250 lines. Parses frontmatter, headings, fenced code, lists, quotes, thematic breaks, and arbitrary-depth directive blocks via colon-counting.
:::

:::card{title="src/inline.ts"}
Tiny inline markup parser. Two entry points: `inlineToHtml` and `inlineToPlain`. Each renderer chooses which to call.
:::

:::card{title="src/renderer-html.ts"}
AST → semantic HTML. Special-cases the typed blocks (claim, evidence, grid, card, plot, agent_task, ...) and falls through to a generic wrapper for unknown directive names.
:::

:::card{title="src/renderer-llm.ts"}
AST → deterministic plain text with `[TAG attr=value]` markers. Designed to maximize signal density inside LLM context windows.
:::

:::card{title="src/validator.ts"}
AST → diagnostics list. Detects duplicate IDs, broken references, plots without data, figures without alt text. Optional schema rules (e.g., claims-need-evidence) are flag-gated.
:::

:::card{title="src/cli.ts"}
The `noma parse|render|check|export` command-line entry. Glue, no logic.
:::

:::card{title="themes/default.css"}
The HTML renderer is theme-agnostic — it only emits semantic class names. The default theme is a single CSS file with custom properties for easy reskinning.
:::
::

## Why no plugin system (yet)

::claim{id="claim-no-plugins-mvp" confidence=0.7 noverify}
A plugin system at v0.1 would harden block semantics before we know which blocks matter. Better to evolve the core typed-block set in lockstep with the renderer until the shape of "real" Noma documents is clear.
::

A plugin API will arrive once three things are true: the AST is stable, two or more independent block packs exist in the wild, and at least one community-contributed renderer ships externally.

## Performance

::result{id="perf-baseline-may-2026"}
On a 1,000-block document the parser runs in roughly 30 ms on a 2024 MacBook Air, and the HTML renderer in roughly 15 ms. No optimization work has been done yet.
::

The parser is hand-written precisely so optimization stays straightforward — if Noma ever needs to render a million-block book in under a second, the path is to port `parser.ts` to a streaming variant or to Rust, without touching the AST or any renderer.

## Conventions

- **One module, one file.** No `utils/` dumping ground.
- **No comments unless the *why* is non-obvious.** Identifiers carry the *what*.
- **TypeScript strict mode.** `noUncheckedIndexedAccess` is on — array access returns `T | undefined`.
- **No build step in development.** `tsx` runs TypeScript directly. `npm run build` exists for the published npm package.
